Students Can Now Reserve Stadium Tracks and Tennis Courts

As of September 1, SMUHSD students are able to reserve District stadium tracks and tennis courts at Aragon, Burlingame, Hillsdale and San Mateo High Schools.

Monday - Friday from 3:30 - 8:30 p.m. is reserved for students only. Members of the public will not be able to reserve the above fields and courts during those days/times.

All students using the facilities need to wear a face covering prior to check in and will be health screened upon entry and required to present their student ID or class schedule to confirm their status as an SMUHSD student.

Individual registration links for the stadium tracks and tennis courts will be listed by school site and students can reserve time at any school site.

https://www.smuhsd.org/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&DomainID=4&ModuleInstanceID=16&ViewID=6446EE88-D30C-497E-9316-3F8874B3E108&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=30886&PageID=1

One of the most important lessons Sophie Abitbol learned during the Stanford course "Teaching Your Class Online: Essentials and Practice" was to keep things simple ‚Äì technology-wise ‚Äì when she welcomes students into their virtual classroom this fall.

‚ÄúWe have to be realistic and start with what we know, which is teaching and kids,‚Äù said Abitbol, who teaches English to 9th and 12th graders at Burlingame High School, a public high school in Burlingame, California. ‚ÄúThe technology bells and whistles will follow.‚Äù

The San Mateo County School Board Association Board of Directors would like to invite all interested parties to join an SMCSBA Town Hall on Monday, July 20 at 6:00 pm.

Hear from School Board Members, Superintendents, Union Leadership and Teachers about school re-opening plans and the many factors that are being considered as districts balance the health, safety, well-being, education and needs of students, staff, and families during the COVID19 pandemic.

Parents, guardians, teachers, administrators, and school board members are welcome to join the call. Please feel free to share the meeting information with your communities. You can submit questions and comments for the Town Hall at this website.

San Mateo High Red Cross Club Co-presidents Steven Huang and Shivum Kapoor recently initiated a volunteering event called Match The Mask.

Match The Mask partnered up with the local Mills-Peninsula Hospital to lead a team of more than 50 volunteers to create masks for the medical community.

Steven and Shivum, on behalf of San Mateo High, recently accepted two Red Cross awards at a Liaison meeting for clubs within the west bay (San Francisco and San Mateo Counties).

The SMHS Red Cross Club received the "Takes Most Initiative" and "Most Engaged Club" awards.

Thanks to all the volunteers including those pictured: Banon Bolander- SMHS ‚Äò21, Madeline Skowronek - HHS ‚Äò22, Lesley Avila Rojas- SMHS Alumni, Anya Higashionna- SMHS ‚Äò22, Steven Huang- SMHS ‚Äò21, and Ray Lui- SMHS ‚Äò21.

Credit Recovery

Your morning pick me up brought to you by the Wind Ensemble at Burlingame High School:

Kyoko Yamamoto, Director of Bands at BHS:

"I am very proud of my Wind Ensemble students for completing this project that we have been working on during the distant learning.

I instructed my wind ensemble students to video record themselves playing along with the audio track of Mambo. We were going to play Mambo as an encore at the spring concert inviting parents and school staff to join as a musician.

I wanted this project to keep encouraging students to play and to give joy to whomever watching the video."

This performance is dedicated to the graduating seniors!

https://youtu.be/-H3ryG6JZzk

San Mateo Union High School District added a new photo.
May 6 at 8:06 PM ¬∑

Hillsdale High School (HHS) student Matt Stewart (pictured top left) is really into 3D printing. Since distance learning started, his HHS advisor Emily Witkop has reported that Matt has been making surgical mask straps using his 3D printer. As you know, all healthcare providers now have to wear surgical masks all day and the plastic strap that Matt has been making protect the back of the ears from chronic wear abrasions.

Do you have a 3D printer and want to help out? Check with your local hospital to see if they have a need and visit the link to the printing program that Matt is using: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4249113.

Helping Hands is a non-profit organization created to slow the spread of COVID-19 through tech-enabled, community volunteerism.

Helping Hands connects people who must shelter in place with those who can safely deliver critical items (like food medicine, or household goods) and provide various forms of assistance (like dog-walking, mail pick-ups, or conversations). By facilitating these connections, we can help protect neighbors from contracting severe illness, and each other from an overwhelmed healthcare system.

Learn more: https://helpinghands.community/

post_text:
Hillsdale High Senior Receives CTE Scholarship

The California Association of Leaders for Career Preparation (CALCP) recently announced that Hillsdale High School Senior Amy Bruhns was the recipient of a 2020 Career Technical Education scholarship.

Hillsdale High School Drama Allison Gamlen nominated Amy for the scholarship and this is what she had to say about her: "She's an incredibly hard working student and in addition to being a triple threat Amy is also a playwright, director, and designed all the fight choreography in SHE KILLS MONSTERS."

A recording of She Kills Monster is available to view until May: https://vimeo.com/401046243/839e47b5ea?fbclid=IwAR3O1t3H6TiTTF8o2OtXkfQ0EKGA3PPa_oe6o9IwUr2k3x0m37-3GMlGaCQ

Amy is the only student in the county to be awarded this honor and she plans to study acting at Pace University in NYC in the Fall.

Learn more: https://www.calcp.org/scholarships/

"16-year-old Eric Gan bears gifts: boxes of donated books. The junior at San Mateo‚Äôs Aragon High School founded Books4All three years ago to inspire children to read.

So far, the teenager has given away more than a thousand new and used books, some of which come from family and friends. He has purchased the rest online using $7,500 he‚Äôs raised. Of that, Eric himself has contributed about $5,000, thanks to his musical talent.

He performs an annual benefit concert in San Mateo and he donates his prize winnings from regional piano competitions as well as his earnings from tutoring."

How Are You Dealing with COVID-19?

The COVID-19 pandemic is having a wide-spread and significant impact on many aspects of daily life. The San Mateo County Psychological Association (SMCPA) recognizes the emotional impact that our community is experiencing and wants to help.

Please join SMCPA for a series of free Virtual Town Hall meetings where a mental health professional will offer tips on coping with stress, managing change, supporting your children and teens, and other relevant topics. They will also answer questions about how to maintain psychological well-being and support one another during these challenging times.

Sunday, April 5, 2020 at 4:30 p.m. PDT
https://zoom.us/meeting/register/upIsfuCoqD0qlqgO_lpHp-jj_WPu8ivRGw

Thursday, April 9, 2020 at 4:30 p.m. PDT
https://zoom.us/meeting/register/uZMsdOCsqzopnuclHh5F4toHI2KdCQvgYQ

After registering, you will receive a confirmation email containing information about joining the meeting.

More virtual meeting dates are in the works. Stay tuned!

Email drstacychiang@gmail.com or rremigio@camdencenter.com with any questions.

Great opinion piece in the San Mateo Daily Journal by Burlingame High's Jacob Lubarsky: Experiences through interactions.

"All of them needed to work several more hours per day than the average working adult to pay for rent, child support and other bills while making not much more than the minimum wage. I, on the other hand, just went in to make money that in reality I did not desperately need; I could quit any time and would face no economic backlash as a result. It took months for me to truly understand the privileges I had largely taken for granted."

Read more: http://ow.ly/KqW650yO7xM

Yesterday, 21 of Aragon High's Art of Video and Digital Photography students toured the ABC7 News studio with their teacher Nick Carrillo, CTE/Career Coordinator Helen O'Brien, and Angela Castillo and Caroline Moala of the Counseling Office.

The morning started with a tour of the offices and a quick Q&A session with an executive producer, who talked about his path to landing in San Francisco. The students then went to the live studio and watched the 11 o'clock (mid-day) news being produced right in front of them...featuring Anchor Reggie Aqui and Aragon Alum Kristen Sze.

Both Reggie and Kristen stayed after the broadcast to answer questions of students. The students were very engaged during the entire field trip and asked some great questions.

San Mateo High School Student David Yang was announced as the winner of the 2020 San Mateo County Poetry Out Loud Competition on February 8.

David advances to the State Finals in Sacramento, March 15-16.

The competition, administered by the San Mateo County Arts Commission, is an initiative of the National Endowment for the Arts, administered statewide by the California Arts Council.

Poetry Out Loud encourages high school students to learn about great poetry through memorization, performance and competition.

Students! Participate in the #Census2020 Arts Showcase

To help motivate everyone to participate in the Census 2020 count, the San Mateo County Office of Education is inviting all San Mateo County students to create artwork with a theme of ‚ÄúWhy I Count‚Äù and share it with the community at their annual event, The Next Big Think!

Who: All San Mateo County Students in grades TK through 12 are invited to participate.

What: Any type of visual, performing or media art piece. You can submit a drawing, painting, photograph, dance performance, song, video, sculpture ‚Äì the choice is yours!

Theme: Your submission should focus on one of the following themes: Why I Count, Why My Family Counts, Why My Community Counts.

When: March 1 is the deadline for all submissions. Performance art entrants may be selected to perform on March 15.

Details: https://www.smcoe.org/for-communities/2020-census.html#arts

Monday, February 3, 7 - 8:30 p.m.

What Every Parent Should Know About Vaping

The San Mateo Main Library will host a conversation with Stanford's Dr. Halpern-Felsher on the dangers of e-cigarettes among youth from 7-8:30 p.m. on Monday, Feb. 3 in the Oak Room, 55 W. Third Ave.

Reports show adolescents and young adults are using e-cigarettes more often than combustible cigarettes.

Dr. Halpern-Felsher will discuss her research on young people‚Äôs perceptions of these products, evidence-based resources that can help prevent and reduce youth use, and what every parent should know about the dangers of vaping.

Via The City of San Mateo:

Support Democracy - Election Workers Needed

Students: Participate by signing up for the Student Democracy Program: https://www.smcacre.org/post/apply-join-student-democracy-program

The March 3, 2020 Presidential Primary Election is fast approaching and the San Mateo County Registration & Elections Division is looking for community service-oriented people to help out. The Elections Office is recruiting for a variety of positions that include helping at Vote Centers, testing elections equipment, processing ballots and administrative assistance. The office is also seeking multi-lingual staff to work at Vote Centers, particularly those who speak Spanish, Chinese, Korean or Tagalog. There are also opportunities for students through the Student Democracy Program! Find out how you can contribute toward our democracy by becoming an election worker with the San Mateo County elections division.

shared_text:
San Mateo County Office of Education
January 17 at 4:30 PM ¬∑

Approximately 40 million people worldwide have been forced into human trafficking, 26 percent of whom are under the age of 18. More often than not, these victims include children in the foster care and juvenile justice systems, youth who have run away or are homeless, and children without lawful immigration status.

To address this issue, SMCOE and its partners help school staff recognize warning signs and support students of concern. Learn more at http://bit.ly/2TzONtE.

#HumanTraffickingPrevention

The last day to register for the GATE Parent Group's SAT CLASS is January 18 and the first day of class is January 25. This class targets the March 14, 2020 test:.

The GATE Parents Group sponsors SAT Preparation Classes several times a year, taught by SMUHSD teachers. Classes are also open to non-SMUHSD students.

Details
Classes are held at at San Mateo High.
Saturdays: 1/25, 2/8, 2/22, 2/29 & 3/7 (skipping 2/1 & 2/15)
Register for Morning Sessions (8:30am-noon) OR Afternoon Sessions (1pm-4:30pm)

For more information and to register, please visit www.gateparents.com or email SAT@gateparents.com Important: Students must registration to take the actual tests.

A limited number of scholarships are available for the SAT Exam Prep for SMUHSD students on a first come first serve basis for households with demonstrated financial need. Applications are due two weeks prior to the start of class. Scholarship application: https://www.gateparents.com/display?action=display&key=73

Save the dates!

San Mateo High School Presents Anything Goes January 31- February 9

One of the most popular musicals of all time brings you romantic hijinks on the high seas as best pals Reno Sweeney and Billy Crocker look for true love aboard a luxury ocean liner, while small time crook Moonface Martin tries to avoid spending this voyage in the brig.

The inimitable Cole Porter score is jammed with hit songs, including "I Get a Kick Out of You," "You're the Top", "It's Delovely," and "Friendship." Directed by Brad Friedman, musical direction by Attilio Tribuzi, and choreography by Robyn Tribuzi.

Learn more: http://smhsdrama.org/anything-goes/

One of the most popular musicals of all time brings you romantic hijinks on the high seas as best pals Reno Sweeney and Billy Crocker look for true love aboard a luxury ocean liner, while small time crook Moonface Martin tries to avoid spending this voyage in the brig.

The inimitable Cole Porter score is jammed with hit songs, including "I Get a Kick Out of You," "You're the Top", "It's Delovely," and "Friendship." Directed by Brad Friedman, musical direction by Attilio Tribuzi, and choreography by Robyn Tribuzi.

Learn more: http://smhsdrama.org/anything-goes/

Save the Date! Capuchino's Thespian Club Presents This Random World "The Myth of Serendipity"

We want to believe that serendipity brings us together, but is that just a myth? Mining the comedy of missed connections, THIS RANDOM WORLD asks the serious question of how often we travel parallel paths through the world without noticing. From an ailing woman who plans one final trip, to her daughter planning one great escape and her son falling prey to a prank gone wrong, this funny, intimate, and heartbreaking play explores the lives that may be happening just out of reach of our own.

Showtimes:
Friday, January 10: 7 p.m.
Saturday, January 11: 7 p.m.
Sunday, January 12: 1 p.m.

Tickets will be available for purchase at the door.

post_text:
California Academy of Sciences now recruiting teens for its Teen Advocates for Science Communication (TASC) program.

TASC is a volunteer program that invites youth in grades 9-12 from across the Bay Area to lead interactive science experiences for Academy visitors and the general public.

Trained by their peers and guided by experts in science and education, TASC volunteers learn to facilitate fun activities that deepen science understanding and inspire passion for nature conservation. In TASC, youth build confidence, strengthen communication skills, and develop lifelong friendships. The

Leadership Design Team (LDT) is a group of highly motivated and experienced TASC volunteers who design TASC public floor experiences, lead activity trainings, and serve in additional leadership roles.

To be eligible for TASC, applicants must:

*Be currently enrolled in 9th -12th grade
*Commit to one program day per week
*Have an interest in science and the natural world

Deadline to apply is January 3, 2020: https://www.calacademy.org/teen-advocates-for-science-communication-tasc

Congratulations to BHS/SMHS Chamber Singers, Clay Hawkins, Amit Krishnan, Uma Labouisse, Kate Mitchell, and Lynne Zeng, who auditioned for and were selected to participate in the California Choral Directors Association (CCDA) California Coastal Regional Honor Choir at SMHS, November 21-23, 2019. 290 students from Eureka to Santa Barbara auditioned and qualified over hundreds of students and were on campus this weekend. Steve Weigant, Districtwide Facility Maintenance Foreperson, has been selected as the Classified Golden Apple recipient for November. Steve was nominated by Brad Barncord, and this is what he had to say about him:

He goes above and beyond on treating the District as his own personal clients- He is passionate about his trade and mentors fellow team members on trade best practices. Steve has been with the District for 17 years and is also an accomplished musician. Most importantly he cares and wants to make a difference."

Congratulations Steve!

Coming soon to the Aragon Theatre is the comedy classic "Young Frankenstein, the Musical". Inspired by the legendary Mel Brooks film, this monster of a musical is sure to bring your funny bone to life. Grandson of the infamous Victor Frankenstein, Frederick Frankenstein inherits his family's estate in Transylvania. With the help of a hunchbacked sidekick, Igor and a pretty lab assistant, Inga, and the old housekeeper, Frau Blucher, Frederick finds himself in the mad scientist shoes of his ancestors.

Performances run from November 21-23 at 7 p.m. and November 24 at 2 p.m.

Get your tickets at www.aragondrama.com, or at the door.

Internship Opportunity!

If you are a student living in the 14th District and would like to intern in Congresswoman Speier's Washington, DC or San Mateo office, visit her website to find out how to apply: https://speier.house.gov/services/internships

Positions in the Washington, DC and San Mateo offices are available starting in June and provide valuable hands-on experience in a Congressional office and a greater understanding of the legislative process. Internships are unpaid positions, however current students may be eligible to receive academic credit.

Deadline to apply for Spring 2020 Internships: December 20, 2019.

post_text:
Mills Drama presents their Fall Play - Noises Off - November 14 - 16!

Noises Off is one of the great comedic plays of all time. Winner of the Drama Desk Award for Best Play, Noises Off is about a group of actors and their director, struggling to put on a silly British farce. We join these theatrical people at the final dress rehearsal, again a month later, and at the end of the show's run. We not only get to see their play hilariously deteriorate, we get to see their backstage antics and insecurities, their character flaws, and their attempts to sabotage the play and each other. Join the Mills community in this legendary play, called by the New York Times: "The greatest farce every written."

Showtimes:
Thursday, November 14: 7:00 p.m.
Friday, November 15: 7:00 p.m.
Saturday, November 16: 2:00 p.m. and 7:00 p.m.

Tickets sold at the door!

Are you a student and feel like adults don‚Äôt understand you and won‚Äôt listen to you? Do you have friends who are struggling and you don‚Äôt know how to help? Are you a parent seeing that your child is depressed but you don‚Äôt know how to help her move forward? You are not alone. In California, 12% of youth reported at least one major depressive episode in the last year. In San Mateo County, we have some of the highest rates of teen hospitalizations for mental health-related issues in the state.

Please join Congresswoman Speier, students, school administrators, and mental health professionals for a panel conversation titled ‚ÄúLearning to Listen: Youth Perspectives on Mental Health.‚Äù
